ndian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"York","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of York in northern England. The surname is now widespread throughout England. Originally, the city bore the Latin name <i>Eburacum</i>, which is probably from a Brittonic name meaning ‘yew-tree place’. This was altered by folk etymology to Old English <i>Eoforwīc</i> (from the elements <i>eofor</i> ‘wild boar’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘specialized farmstead’). This name was taken over by Scandinavian settlers, who altered it back to opacity in the form <i>Jórvík</i> or <i>Jórk</i> (English <i>York</i>, which became finally settled as the placename in the 13th century). The surname has also been adopted by Jews as an Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames.","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of the East Slavic patronymic   Yurkovich   or its Croatian, Slovak, or Slovenian variants. Compare   Yurk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Yurkovich","meanings":["Ukrainian (standard transliteration <b>Yurkovych</b>) and Belorussian: patronymic from the personal name   Yurko   and its Belorussian equivalent <i>Yurka</i>, pet forms of Ukrainian <i>Yuriy</i> and Belorussian <i>Yuray</i>, equivalents of Greek <i>Geōrgios</i> (see   George  ).","Americanized form of Croatian <b>Jurković</b>, Slovak and Slovenian <b>Jurkovič</b> (see   Jurkovic  , compare   Jurkovich   and   Yurkovic  ).","Jewish (from Bessarabia): habitational name for someone from Yurkovtsy in Ukraine."]},{"name":"Yorke","meanings":["English: variant of   York  ."]},{"name":"Yorks","meanings":["English: variant of   York  ."]}]},{"name":"Petronilla","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old female name; an Italian diminutive formed from Pietro, i.e. Peter."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":98,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":107,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Petronilla de York was born in 1117, in Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England. She had at least 1 son with Eldredus Plumpton. She died in Somme, Picardie, France."},"et":{"1117–":"1117–Surnud","1107–Male":"1107–Surnud","1133–Male":"1133–Surnud","1117–Female":"1117–Surnud","1107":"1107","1117":"1117","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1133":"1133","Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1117–":"1117–Kuollut","1107–Male":"1107–Kuollut","1133–Male":"1133–Kuollut","1117–Female":"1117–Kuollut","1107":"1107","1117":"1117","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1133":"1133","Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1117–":"